In [46]:
from tensorflow.keras.layers import Conv2D, MaxPooling2D, Flatten, Dense

model = tf.keras.models.Sequential()
model.add(Conv2D(32,(3,3),activation= 'relu', input_shape=(128,128,3)))
model.add(MaxPooling2D(2,2))
model.add(Conv2D(64,(5,5),activation= 'relu'))
model.add(MaxPooling2D(2,2))
model.add(Flatten())
model.add(Dense(n_classes,activation= 'softmax'))
In [47]:
opt =  tf.keras.optimizers.Adam(lr=1e-3)
In [48]:
model.compile(loss='categorical_crossentropy',optimizer= opt, metrics = ['accuracy'])

The convolutional layers create feature maps that record a region of image which is ultimately broken into rectangles and sent out for nonlinear processing. IT has very High accuracy in image recognition problems. They reduce the number of units in the network (since they are many-to-one mappings).This means, there are fewer parameters to learn which reduces the chance of overfitting as the model would be less complex than a fully connected network.

Neural Networks can have a large number of free parameters (the weights and biases between interconnected units) and this gives them the flexibility to fit highly complex data (when trained correctly) that other models are too simple to fit.
